

Urban Mobility Data Explorer — Technical Report



1. Problem Framing and Dataset Analysis
We worked with the NYC TLC Yellow Taxi trip records for January 2019. The dataset has close to 7.7 million rows and covers every yellow taxi trip made in New York City that month, including pickup and dropoff times, locations, distances, fares, and tips. We also used a zone lookup table with 265 zones to map numeric location IDs to real borough and zone names.
Cleaning the data involved four checks. First, rows missing any of the four core fields — pickup time, dropoff time, distance, or fare — were dropped. Second, trips in which the pickup year was not 2019 or the dropoff time came before the pickup time were removed as temporal violations. Third, trips with zero or negative fares, zero or negative distances, or distances above 100 miles were filtered out as physically impossible. Fourth, we calculated the average speed for each trip and removed anything above 80 mph as a sensor error.
We assumed that any trip from a year other than 2019 was an error in the source file, that 100 miles is an unrealistic upper limit for a city taxi trip, and that 80 mph is too fast for any legitimate taxi in urban traffic. We defined rush hour as weekday mornings from 7 to 9 AM and weekday afternoons from 4 to 7 PM, which matches how NYC transportation planners define peak periods.
The unexpected observation was how little data we actually lost. After running all four cleaning stages on 7,667,792 records, we kept 7,599,722 of them — a retention rate of 99.11%. We expected a much messier dataset. What was especially surprising was that zero records failed the spatial check, meaning every single trip in the file referenced a valid zone ID. This gave us confidence that the insights from the dashboard were based on a genuine and representative sample of NYC taxi activity.

2. System Architecture and Design Decisions
The system has three layers. The data pipeline reads and cleans the raw CSV, then saves the result as a parquet file. The backend reads that Parquet file, loads it into a SQLite database, and serves it through a Flask REST API. The frontend is a plain HTML page that fetches data from the API and renders charts using Chart.js.
